Review: At 20:22 their animation is not how the plane crashed. It came straight down at an angle (nose first) digging a long trench. This is the fault of Airbus and their inexperience of designing airplanes. This never happened on a Boeing, whether totally mechanical linkage/hydraulic controls or fly-by-wire. It also [likely] showed the inherent fracture nature of composite polymer/fiber aviation structures. While stronger and lighter than aluminum, they can behave like aluminum 15 to 20 years after an aluminum plane's delivery to an airline; After a aluminum fatigue crack has grown to the point of near failure. This has been explained by many people (such as the Boeing engineer who blew the whistle on the 787 revealing that the upon a crash or impact scenario, the malleability of aluminum was more survivable upon impact than composite aircraft structures). The A300 was the first commercial airplane in the world to utilize composite materials, and despite it's good overall safety record, was a test in these new aircraft material technologies. Airbus covered up these flaws which caused the aircraft to break up, as did the American NTSB who minimized these facts as a "minor contributor". The issue is the that composites while overall stronger and lighter than aluminum, shatter upon impact, or when exposed to structural forces beyond physical limits/design limits. No pilot should ever be able to exert so much force on controls/control surfaces, that it causes airplanes (parts/control surfaces) to break apart. The Boeing engineer stated that it's only a matter of time, before we again see how and why composites are vulnerable when it creates a death toll more survivable in an aluminum body aircraft. As to why NASA and the NTSB covered it up, I believe it's because American aircraft and rocketry manufacturers utilize composite materials in the design and construction of their commercial, fighter, and space aircraft. And that they have justified that the positives outweigh the negatives of a rare aircraft accident. The issue with composites is therefore multi-faceted. From sheared/fractured connections to shattered fuselage upon crashing to far more plastic and therefore a far more flammable and toxic structure in a fire; To far less lightening protection on composite airplanes. Carbon fiber composite shatters and tears. Aluminum can also, but it predominately crumples or bends during exposure to extreme forces or impact.  As for me, if I ever fly again, I will try to fly on legacy aircraft such as 767, 777, or other such planes.  https://bit.ly/2Hhgu4P https://bit.ly/2Fabn4g https://bit.ly/2Ck8Hzd https://bit.ly/2u3Fiof https://bit.ly/2u3Pzkt https://bit.ly/2Hs7ER0 http://tinyurl.com/yxpttjbw

Title: American Airlines - Airbus A300-600 - Takeoff from Guatemala City
Author: musico81986
Description: This is a re-edited video in high definition of my previous video I had. American Airlines flight 928 from Guatemala City to Miami, onboard an Airbus A300-600. Includes preboarding, boarding, taxi, and takeoff. From the terminal, you can see the VOR transmitter (114.5 MHZ). Note how close the airplane comes to the adjacent hangars during taxi. You can also see the "Water Volcano" in the background. After takeoff, you can see "El Obelisco", the main roundabout where main roads in Guatemala meet. I ommited push-back and initial taxi run because there was a lot of condensation on my window. Apperantely this A300 flies in the night before, and stays overnight for the morning flight-out. You can see the condensation breaking away on my window. Sorry about that. I also do NOT have my arrival into guatemala because I arrived early in the morning when its dark. I was sitting across from the flight attendants and they noticed my camera and warned me to keep it off when told. Next time, I'll pick a day-flight! Enjoy!

Title: American Airlines - Airbus A300-600 - Takeoff from Guatemala City
Author: musico81986
Description: This is a re-edited video in high definition of my previous video I had. American Airlines flight 928 from Guatemala City to Miami, onboard an Airbus A300-600. Includes preboarding, boarding, taxi, and takeoff. From the terminal, you can see the VOR transmitter (114.5 MHZ). Note how close the airplane comes to the adjacent hangars during taxi. You can also see the "Water Volcano" in the background. After takeoff, you can see "El Obelisco", the main roundabout where main roads in Guatemala meet. I ommited push-back and initial taxi run because there was a lot of condensation on my window. Apperantely this A300 flies in the night before, and stays overnight for the morning flight-out. You can see the condensation breaking away on my window. Sorry about that. I also do NOT have my arrival into guatemala because I arrived early in the morning when its dark. I was sitting across from the flight attendants and they noticed my camera and warned me to keep it off when told. Next time, I'll pick a day-flight! Enjoy!
